<section xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude" xml:id="s_bases_top">
  <title>Bases for topological spaces</title>
  <introduction>
    <p>
    When defining a topology <m>\mathcal{T}</m> for a set <m>X</m> it is often convenient to specify instead a more manageable subset of <m> \mathcal{T}</m> that we can use to <em>generate</em> the entire topology using arbitrary unions and/or finite intersections (our open set operators). A <em>topological basis</em> is a particularly nice example of this (<xref ref="d_basis" text="global"/>) as the open sets of the topology it generates can be expressed as (arbitrary) unions of the basis elements. Bases will also provide a convenient way of comparing different topologies and (later on) determining whether relevant topological properties are satisfied by a given space.
    </p>
</introduction>
<definition xml:id="d_basis">
  <title>Topological basis</title>
  <statement>
    Let <m>X</m> be a set. A <term>(topological) basis</term> in <m>X</m> is a collection <m>\mathcal{B}</m> of subsets of <m>X</m> satisfying the following axioms:
    <ol>
      <li>
        <title>Covers <m>X</m></title>
        <p>
          For each <m>x\in X</m> there is a set <m>B\in \mathcal{B}</m> such that <m>x\in B</m>.
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <title>Intersections covered by basis elements</title>
        <p>
          If <m>B_1, B_2\in \mathcal{B}</m>, then for all <m>x\in B_1\cap B_2</m> there is a <m>B\in \mathcal{B}</m> such that <m>x\in B\subseteq B_1\cap B_2</m>.
        </p>
      </li>
    </ol>
  </statement>
</definition>
<example xml:id="eg_basis_R">
  <title>Some bases for <m>\R</m></title>
  <statement>
    <p>
      Show that the given collections <m>\mathcal{B}</m> are bases in <m>\R</m>.
    </p>
    <ol>
      <li>
        <p>
          <m>\mathcal{B}_1=\{(x-\epsilon, x+\epsilon)\colon x,\epsilon\in \R, \epsilon&gt; 0\}</m>
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          <m>\mathcal{B}_2=\{(a,b)\colon a,b\in \R, a&lt; b\}</m>
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          <m>\mathcal{B}_3=\{ (p,q)\colon p,q\in \Q, p&lt; q\} </m>
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          <m>\mathcal{B}_4=\{[a,b)\colon a,b\in \R, a&lt; b\}</m>
        </p>
      </li>
    </ol>
  </statement>
  <solution>
    <p>
      It is clear that each collection of intervals covers <m>\R</m>. As for intersections, for (2)-(3) note that intersection of these types of intervals are either empty, or another interval of the same type. For (1) if <m>B_1=(x-\epsilon_1, x+\epsilon_1)</m>
    </p>
  </solution>
</example>

<theorem xml:id="th_basis_generated">
  <title>Topology generated by basis</title>
  <statement>
    <p>
      Let <m>\mathcal{B}\subseteq \mathcal{P}(X)</m> be a basis in the set <m>X</m>.
    </p>
    <ol>
      <li>
        <p> The set
          <me>
            \mathcal{T}=\{U\subseteq X\colon U=\bigcup_{i\in I}B_i \text{ for some elements } B_i\in \mathcal{B}\}
          </me>
          is a topology on <m>X</m>.
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          We have the following alternate description of <m>\mathcal{T}</m>:
          <me>
            U\in \mathcal{T} \iff \text{ for all } x\in U \ \text{ there exists } B\in \mathcal{B} \text{ such that } x\in B\subseteq U
          </me>.
        </p>
      </li>
    </ol>
  </statement>
</theorem>
<definition xml:id="d_basis_generated">
  <title>Topology generated by basis</title>
  <statement>
    <p>
      Let <m>\mathcal{B}\subseteq \mathcal{P}(X)</m> be a basis in the set <m>X</m>. The topology
      <mdn>
        <mrow xml:id="eq_top_generated1">\mathcal{T}\amp =\{U\subseteq X\colon U=\bigcup_{i\in I}B_i \text{ for some elements } B_i\in \mathcal{B}\} </mrow>
        <mrow xml:id="eq_top_generated2">  \amp = \{U\subseteq X\colon \text{ for all } x\in U \text{ there exists } B\in \mathcal{B} \text{ s.t. } x\in B\subseteq U\}</mrow>
      </mdn>
      is called the <term>topology generated</term> by <m>\mathcal{B}</m>. Similarly, we call <m>\mathcal{B}</m> as basis for <m>\mathcal{T}</m>.
    </p>
  </statement>
</definition>
    <example xml:id="eg_basis_standard_R">
  <title>A basis for the standard topology on <m>\R</m></title>
  <statement>
    <p>
      Observe that the topology <m>\mathcal{T}</m> generated by the basis <m>\mathcal{B}_1</m> in <xref ref="eg_basis_R"/> is precisely the <xref ref="top_eq_standard_R" text='custom'>standard topology on <m>\R</m> </xref>, as the description of <m>\mathcal{T}</m> in <xref ref="eq_top_generated2"/> makes clear.
    </p>
  </statement>
  </example>
<theorem xml:id="th_compare_basis">
  <title>Comparing with bases</title>
  <statement>
    <p>
      Let <m>\mathcal{T}</m> be a topology on <m>X</m> generated by the basis <m>\mathcal{B}</m>.
    </p>
    <ol>
      <li>
        <p>
          Let <m>\mathcal{T}'</m> be a topology on <m>X</m>. We have
          <men xml:id="eq_compare_basis_top">
            \mathcal{T}\subseteq \mathcal{T}'\iff B\in \mathcal{T}' \text{ for all } B\in \mathcal{B}
          </men>.
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          Let <m>\mathcal{T}'</m> be a topology on <m>X</m> generated by the basis <m>\mathcal{B}'</m>. We have
          <men xml:id="eq_compare_basis_basis">
            \mathcal{T}\subseteq \mathcal{T}'\iff \text{ for all } B\in \mathcal{B} \text{ and } x\in B  \text{ there exists } B'\in \mathcal{B}' \text{ s.t. } x\in B'\subseteq B
          </men>.
        </p>
      </li>
    </ol>
  </statement>
</theorem>
